text: I remember DiCaprio talking about global warming when he came to Alberta. He blamed Alberta's warm swing in the middle of winter on global warming. We regularly have warm swings (called Chinooks) which give us a temperature swing of 20 to 30 degrees Centigrade in a matter of hours. It is a direct result of our geographic placement, next to the Eastern Rockies, which redirects high and low pressure systems. There are 3 places in the world with similar geographic attributes which affect weather: the Urals, Mongolian Steppe and South Eastern Alberta. Yet this ignoramous opened up his uneducated and uninformed pie hole and started spewing nonsense about how this temperature swing  is a result of global warming. It pissed everyone off, yet the uninformed fans of this dickhead took it as gospel truth, because it came from a celebrity.  I, and the people I know, have all stayed away from every movie this moron is in. We won't reward his stupidity by contributing to his bank account. Hey DiCaprio: how about you get rid of your mega yacht, because it contributes more to your global warming than our entire small town. Or does your jibberish apply only to us and not you?

text: ¬†@Jonas Suter¬† Socialism as a political frame identified by a generous social safety net and public pension system in which the public services are well founded by a relatively high-tax economy. Norway, Sweden, France, Germany or Danemark as examples encompass different variants and versions. Nordic model or social democracy are just late XX century version of the same social and economical theory. They all integate a social organization which advocates that the means of production, distribution, and exchange should be owned or regulated by their community. Its expression in many european countries is far from what people in the States understand by socialism and is far from what has been experienced during in the USSR. In the US, it looks to be a "bad" word, or filled with negative connotation (= propaganda ?), while in many european countries it is totally more or less understood as being a political organization where most can benefit from the wealth generated by the society.

text:
According to the Vostok Ice Core Records, CO2 level changes have followed Earth's overall temperature changes at an 800 year lag for the last 800,000 years.  That means that our current CO2 levels are the result of Earth's overall temperature 800 years ago.  World leaders have convinced their dependents that this works in the reverse order, relatively quickly, and that we are to blame, so that they can tax us out of a false shared guilt in order to be able to afford to "fight" climate change, an unstoppable natural cycle.  The following is the source of this information:

Historical Carbon Dioxide Record from the Vostok Ice Core

Investigators
J.-M. Barnola, D. Raynaud, C. Lorius
Laboratoire de Glaciologie et de G√©ophysique de l'Environnement,
CNRS, BP96,
38402 Saint Martin d'Heres Cedex, France

N.I. Barkov
Arctic and Antarctic Research Institute,
Beringa Street 38, 199397,
St. Petersburg, Russia

Period of Record
417,160 - 2,342 years BP

Methods
In January 1998, the collaborative ice-drilling project between Russia, the United States, and France at the Russian Vostok station in East Antarctica yielded the deepest ice core ever recovered, reaching a depth of 3,623 m (Petit et al. 1997, 1999). Ice cores are unique with their entrapped air inclusions enabling direct records of past changes in atmospheric trace-gas composition. Preliminary data indicate the Vostok ice-core record extends through four climate cycles, with ice slightly older than 400 kyr (Petit et al. 1997, 1999). Because air bubbles do not close at the surface of the ice sheet but only near the firn-ice transition (that is, at ~90 m below the surface at Vostok), the air extracted from the ice is younger than the surrounding ice (Barnola et al. 1991). Using semiempirical models of densification applied to past Vostok climate conditions, Barnola et al. (1991) reported that the age difference between air and ice may be ~6000 years during the coldest periods instead of ~4000 years, as previously assumed. Ice samples were cut with a bandsaw in a cold room (at about -15¬∞C) as close as possible to the center of the core in order to avoid surface contamination (Barnola et al. 1983). Gas extraction and measurements were performed with the "Grenoble analytical setup," which involved crushing the ice sample (~40 g) under vacuum in a stainless-steel container without melting it, expanding the gas released during the crushing in a pre-evacuated sampling loop, and analyzing the CO2 concentrations by gas chromatography (Barnola et al. 1983). The analytical system, except for the stainless-steel container in which the ice was crushed, was calibrated for each ice sample measurement with a standard mixture of CO2 in nitrogen and oxygen. For further details on the experimental procedures and the dating of the successive ice layers at Vostok, see Barnola et al. (1987, 1991), Lorius et al. (1985), and Petit et al. (1999).

Trends
There is a close correlation between Antarctic temperature and atmospheric concentrations of CO2 (Barnola et al. 1987). The extension of the Vostok CO2 record shows that the main trends of CO2 are similar for each glacial cycle. Major transitions from the lowest to the highest values are associated with glacial-interglacial transitions. During these transitions, the atmospheric concentrations of CO2 rises from 180 to 280-300 ppmv (Petit et al. 1999). The extension of the Vostok CO2 record shows the present-day levels of CO2 are unprecedented during the past 420 kyr. Pre-industrial Holocene levels (~280 ppmv) are found during all interglacials, with the highest values (~300 ppmv) found approximately 323 kyr BP. When the Vostok ice core data were compared with other ice core data (Delmas et al. 1980; Neftel et al. 1982) for the past 30,000 - 40,000 years, good agreement was found between the records: all show low CO2 values [~200 parts per million by volume (ppmv)] during the Last Glacial Maximum and increased atmospheric CO2 concentrations associated with the glacial-Holocene transition. According to Barnola et al. (1991) and Petit et al. (1999) these measurements indicate that, at the beginning of the deglaciations, the CO2 increase either was in phase or lagged by less than ~1000 years with respect to the Antarctic temperature, whereas it clearly lagged behind the temperature at the onset of the glaciations.

References
Barnola, J.-M., D. Raynaud, A. Neftel, and H. Oeschger. 1983. Comparison of CO2 measurements by two laboratories on air from bubbles in polar ice. Nature 303:410-13.

Barnola, J.-M., D. Raynaud, Y.S. Korotkevich, and C. Lorius. 1987. Vostok ice core provides 160,000-year record of atmospheric CO2. Nature 329:408-14.

Barnola, J.-M., P. Pimienta, D. Raynaud, and Y.S. Korotkevich. 1991. CO2-climate relationship as deduced from the Vostok ice core: A re-examination based on new measurements and on a re-evaluation of the air dating. Tellus 43(B):83- 90.

Delmas, R.J., J.-M. Ascencio, and M. Legrand. 1980. Polar ice evidence that atmospheric CO2 20,000 yr BP was 50% of present. Nature 284:155-57.

Jouzel, J., C. Lorius, J.R. Petit, C. Genthon, N.I. Barkov, V.M. Kotlyakov, and V.M. Petrov. 1987. Vostok ice core: A continuous isotopic temperature record over the last climatic cycle (160,000 years). Nature 329:403-8.

Lorius, C., J. Jouzel, C. Ritz, L. Merlivat, N.I. Barkov, Y.S. Korotkevich, and V.M. Kotlyakov. 1985. A 150,000-year climatic record from Antarctic ice. Nature 316:591-96.

Neftel, A., H. Oeschger, J. Schwander, B. Stauffer, and R. Zumbrunn. 1982. Ice core measurements give atmospheric CO2 content during the past 40,000 yr. Nature 295:220-23.

Pepin, L., D. Raynaud, J.-M. Barnola, and M.F. Loutre. 2001. Hemispheric roles of climate forcings during glacial-interglacial transitions as deduced from the Vostok record and LLN-2D model experiments. Journal of Geophysical Research 106 (D23): 31,885-31,892.

Petit, J.R., I. Basile, A. Leruyuet, D. Raynaud, C. Lorius, J. Jouzel, M. Stievenard, V.Y. Lipenkov, N.I. Barkov, B.B. Kudryashov, M. Davis, E. Saltzman, and V. Kotlyakov. 1997. Four climate cycles in Vostok ice core. Nature 387: 359-360.

P√©pin, C. Ritz, E. Saltzman, and M. Stievenard. 1999. Climate and atmospheric history of the past 420,000 years from the Vostok ice core, Antarctica. Nature 399: 429-436.

Raynaud, D., and J.-M. Barnola. 1985. An Antarctic ice core reveals atmospheric CO2 variations over the past few centuries. Nature 315:309-11.

text:
How To Reduce Pollution 

1. Many Production Companies Has To Be Stopped

From global warming or climate change there is going to be mass extinctions of humans and wildlife, we do not know when, but from pollution also we are going to face mass extinction.
We manufacture so many products and it is creating pollution and pollution has increased to such an extent that it has become a threat to the world. So if we minimise our products, pollution would be less.
We produce so many things which we do not need as a necessity, like cold drinks, leather products, potato wafers, chips, fruit juices, chocolates, biscuits, pickles, ice creams, etc. 
Cold drinks, fruit juices, chocolates, biscuits, pickles, ice creams, etc. should be cooked at home only. Instead of cold drinks people should drink natural drinks such as lime water, coconut water or just any fruit, not any fruit juice, just the whole fruit which can be served when a customer comes in a shop, hotel or a person selling this drinks on a street and serve it to him. If we stopped producing this things which are not required as a necessity for humans, so much pollution could be reduced.
What about the companies that are going to be shut down. They would have debts to pay, just excuse them.
If we colour the clothes pollution occurs. So if we don't colour our clothes, the pollution resulting from colouring the clothes can be stopped. Let everything remain in white natural colour. 

2. We Should Cook Foods In Its Natural Form

We can cook rice and wheat in our homes and eat it. Rice and Wheat is produced in farms. Then it is packed and transported to big warehouses, then wholesalers buy from them and supply to retail shops. 
But if a manufacturing company makes bread from rice and wheat, then to make bread a manufacturing company has to be set up, machines and working staffs are needed. When a company is built many other things are also needed. Then at last a plastic pack is required to pack the breads.
So if we start cooking eatable things in its natural form then we do not need many companies like bread manufacturing company, tomato ketchup, noodles, fruit jam, pizza, burger, etc., the things required for the company and the plastic pack, paper box pack and glass bottles. If done like this, so many companies will not be required and hence less pollution for the world. Humans have to do this before it is too late.

If this is done, then many jobs would be lost. For that many peoples should do farming and they should be given loans if they do not have enough money to start farming on their own. Many people should study botany subject so that they have knowledge of plants and they should do farming.
Is their any another solution, that humans won't lose jobs and also planet earth will be saved.
Industrial jobs or planet earth, which should we save, planet earth is more important. Humans have to take this step certainly instead of going on polluting the earth, making¬† wildlife extinct and also mass extinctions of humans after 100 or 200 years. Humans should not want this to happen.

text: I remember DiCaprio talking about global warming when he came to Alberta. He blamed Alberta's warm swing in the middle of winter on global warming. We regularly have warm swings (called Chinooks) which give us a temperature swing of 20 to 30 degrees Centigrade in a matter of hours. It is a direct result of our geographic placement, next to the Eastern Rockies, which redirects high and low pressure systems. There are 3 places in the world with similar geographic attributes which affect weather: the Urals, Mongolian Steppe and South Eastern Alberta. Yet this ignoramous opened up his uneducated and uninformed pie hole and started spewing nonsense about how this temperature swing  is a result of global warming. It pissed everyone off, yet the uninformed fans of this dickhead took it as gospel truth, because it came from a celebrity.  I, and the people I know, have all stayed away from every movie this moron is in. We won't reward his stupidity by contributing to his bank account. Hey DiCaprio: how about you get rid of your mega yacht, because it contributes more to your global warming than our entire small town. Or does your jibberish apply only to us and not you?

text:
How To Reduce Pollution 

1. Many Production Companies Has To Be Stopped

From global warming or climate change there is going to be mass extinctions of humans and wildlife, we do not know when, but from pollution also we are going to face mass extinction.
We manufacture so many products and it is creating pollution and pollution has increased to such an extent that it has become a threat to the world. So if we minimise our products, pollution would be less.
We produce so many things which we do not need as a necessity, like cold drinks, leather products, potato wafers, chips, fruit juices, chocolates, biscuits, pickles, ice creams, etc. 
Cold drinks, fruit juices, chocolates, biscuits, pickles, ice creams, etc. should be cooked at home only. Instead of cold drinks people should drink natural drinks such as lime water, coconut water or just any fruit, not any fruit juice, just the whole fruit which can be served when a customer comes in a shop, hotel or a person selling this drinks on a street and serve it to him. If we stopped producing this things which are not required as a necessity for humans, so much pollution could be reduced.
What about the companies that are going to be shut down. They would have debts to pay, just excuse them.
If we colour the clothes pollution occurs. So if we don't colour our clothes, the pollution resulting from colouring the clothes can be stopped. Let everything remain in white natural colour. 

2. We Should Cook Foods In Its Natural Form

We can cook rice and wheat in our homes and eat it. Rice and Wheat is produced in farms. Then it is packed and transported to big warehouses, then wholesalers buy from them and supply to retail shops. 
But if a manufacturing company makes bread from rice and wheat, then to make bread a manufacturing company has to be set up, machines and working staffs are needed. When a company is built many other things are also needed. Then at last a plastic pack is required to pack the breads.
So if we start cooking eatable things in its natural form then we do not need many companies like bread manufacturing company, tomato ketchup, noodles, fruit jam, pizza, burger, etc., the things required for the company and the plastic pack, paper box pack and glass bottles. If done like this, so many companies will not be required and hence less pollution for the world. Humans have to do this before it is too late.

If this is done, then many jobs would be lost. For that many peoples should do farming and they should be given loans if they do not have enough money to start farming on their own. Many people should study botany subject so that they have knowledge of plants and they should do farming.
Is their any another solution, that humans won't lose jobs and also planet earth will be saved.
Industrial jobs or planet earth, which should we save, planet earth is more important. Humans have to take this step certainly instead of going on polluting the earth, making¬† wildlife extinct and also mass extinctions of humans after 100 or 200 years. Humans should not want this to happen.

text:
For all the talk about climate change,  even over after 30 years of it,  I have yet to see anything at all 
Being done about it.  You Americans still spend an awful amount of money on the military,  and if Americans 
Were really serious about the problem, then that money on the military, or at least most  of it , should be used
To try to solve the problem instead.  After all, the cost of trying to become less dependent on fossil fuels 
Is going to be huge and not even the most powerful nation in the world can afford to spend huge amounts of money 
Both on its military and on environmental protection measures.  The States has to make a choice, and judging 
By events of the last 2 or 3  decades  or so,  has decided to make military spending more of a priority than the future of civilization.
And it has decided to INCREASE its nuclear warhead arsenal and withdraw from nuclear arms treaties, so with more 
Nuclear missiles being built,  humans may wipe themselves out in a nuclear exchange  before anything else 
Causes the end of civilization.  
It is a depressing thought,  but the end of human society in the not too distant future, meaning in the next 50 to 
100 years or so, probably, but may be sooner than that, is inevitable,  whatever we do.  Considering the endless desperate 
Problems the world has, can one not be blamed for coming to such a bleak conclusion?

text: DiCrappio is an idiot...lol..he came to western Canada and said he experienced global warming first hand when the he was here filming a movie. lol...what he experienced was a Chinook wind. A Chinook wind is an old Native term for strong warm winds that blow in from the west off the pacific ocean over the Rocky Mountains and across the prairies pushing out colder air and bringing in warner air. it can raise the temperature several degrees in a very short period of time. They are very welcome winds that bring a bit of warmth during the winter time and everybody loves when things warm up all of a sudden. This is not Global Warming. This is not human caused. This is nature doing its thing. Even the term Chinook has been around for a hundred years or more. When he was here filming, he told the world that even the locals were terrified of the Chinook winds lol...I have lived here all my life, I have never met anyone who was afraid of warm air blowing in over the mountains and melting the snow several times every winter. Thanks for your thoughts, Dave. 

https://climate.nasa.gov/evidence/

Considering science will never give you 100% certainty, 95% is pretty darn good. Based on international cooperation and sophisticated instrumentation, NASA states there is a 95% likelihood that the phenomena we are observing today is directly related to the activities of mankind.  

This body of evidence is compiled by reviewing paleoclimate trends that span the past several hundred thousand years.  Even when considering weather patterns, on this timescale, scientist can find no better way to explain the weather patterns we are observing today, other than that mankind is a heavy contributor.

text:
¬†@Krishna¬† 
By calahon hanson from Quora :
You‚Äôre not the only one. I agree on a variety of levels.

First, let me acknowledge something: DiCaprio is a competent actor. Not a bad actor, just not exceptional. I would inform this perspective on several levels.

First, Leo has a limited range. Just do an exercise. Pick his five most memorable roles of the 21st century. He‚Äôs an active professional, so everyone‚Äôs list will be different. Now while we could attribute this to his level of activity or consistent memorability, I would attribute this to what I call the ‚Äúhe‚Äôs-an-actor‚Äù paradox. Most people walk in to a DiCaprio movie to be shown something they‚Äôve seen before, not to be shown something new. Leo is consistently proficient at being an ‚Äúactor‚Äù. That‚Äôs the catch-he‚Äôs an actor. The greatest performers of the modern day are able to inhabit characters, rather than imitate or play them. DiCaprio has a decided screen presence, and he retains his physical charm through most roles. But he always carries himself in roughly the same way onscreen. An inherently appealing cinematic presence does not necessarily make for a good actor in various roles. Take his work in Christopher Nolan‚Äôs ‚ÄúInception‚Äù. Can you remember his character‚Äôs name? Besides that he was played by Leonardo DiCaprio, what attributes of his were embodied onscreen to make him an intriguing and worthy protagonist of a Nolan movie? Similarly, name five ways in which DiCaprio presented his character in Inception differently than his character in ‚ÄúShutter Island‚Äù, a Scorcese movie of the same year. How is his performance in ‚ÄúThe Great Gatsby‚Äù different from that in ‚ÄúCatch Me if You Can‚Äù, aside from different costumes? He carries himself in the same way, speaks in the same voice, and gives competent but not overtly memorable performances. Those are just examples of DiCaprio being cast, in some way, as ‚ÄúDiCaprio‚Äù.

Another reason for his lack-of-greatness: he is consistently overshadowed by other truly great performances (or by exterior elements of the film) in movies where he is billed as the lead. This may seem trivial, but most great (or even very good) actors are defined by their ability to be extremely captivating. Examples:

-In ‚ÄúCatch Me if You Can‚Äù, DiCaprio acts in the shadow of the his smooth-talking father(Christopher Walken) for the first hour of the movie. The second half of the movie is much weaker than the first, relying more on Tom Hanks‚Äô stern humor and Amy Adam‚Äôs effective emotional performance.

-Leo‚Äôs first collaboration with Martin Scorcese, Gangs of New York, is best remembered for Daniel Day Lewis‚Äôs outstanding turn as the despicable, gut-wrenching ‚ÄúBill the Butcher‚Äù. The movie is also memorable for the gang-violence featuring the bloody fight between Daniel Day Lewis and Liam Neeson.

-Scorcese‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Departed‚Äù is memorable for the script, Jack Nicholson‚Äôs ‚ÄúI‚Äôve got this rat‚Äù speech, and Mark Wahlberg‚Äôs foul-mouthed Srgt. Dignam. Alec Baldwin also made the most of his few scenes. But DiCaprio was billed as the lead, wasn‚Äôt he?

-The Revenant is memorable for the bear attack, Tom Hardy‚Äôs ‚Äúsquirrel tangent‚Äù, and Emmanuel Lubezki‚Äôs award-winning wide-angle cinematography and visual motifs. DiCaprio‚Äôs mumble-riddled (yet Oscar-winning) performance on its own does not make the movie.

My final case: any actor to be considered great must be able to play a variety of roles convincingly, and there have simply been better character actors out there. In other words, the people who campaign for DiCaprio to garner Oscar Nominations every year should consider the disrespect that pays to the community of excellent character actors. DiCaprio might be a block-buster favorite, but the 21st century has given us numerous character performers more worthy of recognition (and more capable of delivering truly unique and surprising performances). The late Philip Seymour Hoffman, Tom Hanks, Christian Bale, and Denzel Washington are all prime examples of generational actors who made or make any role believable, and are not afraid to take risks as actors. Actors should commit to individual characters, not to being a performer in general. DiCaprio‚Äôs individual roles lack depth, even if his collective body of work might suggest greatness.

In conclusion, I really don‚Äôt have a problem with Leo. He consistently delivers solid, enjoyable performances. I do think that the modern era of popularism has devalued the craftsmanship of many artistic professions, and that DiCaprio‚Äôs almost universal appraisal as a great actor is a perfect thematic representation of this trend.

text:
I'm sorry, but given that we all live on this planet, regardless of borders, politics or whatever man-made crap boundaries, if one looks on the internet for evidence of climate change, all while living on this planet and believes that climate change is a hoax, that person has to be particularly dense..... or an ignorant imbecile plain and simple. In fact, there are people across the world without access to the internet that witness and can attest to the ongoing and worsening climate changes that affect the environment, from waters, to fish, animals, trees, plants, insects, people's livelihoods etc Especially older and intelligent or wise people can attest to the fact that there's something very wrong going on with the environment. They may not have access to the internet or be able to use technology, but they still can see and understand that the climate changes that are taking place are undergoing at an ever accelerated rate. They can compare seasonal changes from their own childhoods or half of their lives with what is going on today. From the disappearance of lakes, rivers, to the disappearance of glaciers that used to be mountain-high and mighty in the youth of their generation, to weather phenomena completely uncharacteristic to one region happening in that region (tornadoes where tornadoes have never formed before, snow where it has never snowed, violent storms, shorter winters etc).
Maybe I lack the patience, but I can't understand how so many people can be so blatantly stupid and ignorant in this day and age in regards to climate change considering the tremendous amount of feedback available to us, from scientists, from the internet and from nature itself ffs! It's like such people are being hit with bricks on a constant basis and yet they deny it's going on...
Also, btw.... denying scientists research results while not having a minimum amount of scientific education and understanding and/or not being a scientist yourself to come with your own proper research is down right stupid and insulting to the scientists that spend their lives actually investigating, researching, checking out what the nay-sayers are not. In other words, for a nay-sayer to make a contradictory statement to a scientific fact while being an utter and complete non-qualified and incompetent in the field is ridiculous....
It's like you would have a person that can't even find a spare tire in a car or figure out what type of fuel the car runs on contradict an engineer or attempt to "teach" the engineer about how cars work..... Maybe I'm naive but I believe that mankind is NOT this freakin idiotic. I believe that in 2016 we have come a long way! And yet reality shows that unfortunately we are not as advanced as we'd like to believe and we are not as smart as we'd like to believe about mankind. There's still a lot of idiocy, idiocracy thrives, there's still a lot of lack of education, and still a lot of ignorance. And considering our technological and scientific achievements and advancements to date and our extraordinary potential, this is exactly why stupidity and ignorance in this day and age should not and must not be tolerated! With so much access to information and learning, especially in regards to developed countries, ignorance and stupidity is voluntary and on a larger scale that can be equated to being criminal.

text:
Thanks for sharing your thoughts. I have to, respectfully, disagree.

https://climate.nasa.gov/evidence/

Scientists appear to be well aware of obliquity, a term used to describe the "wobbling" of the Earth's axis, over a period approximately 44,000 years in length.  Even when considering this and other paleoclimate phenomenon, scientists cannot compensate for the changes we have observed (measured with advanced instruments) over the last several decades.  

Given the sheer scale on which we are measuring climate today, and the international cooperation required to make use of the data we gather, I am hesitant to say this is a part of some global conspiracy.  Science appears to back up claims that the climate changes, that we are observing today, are 95% likely to be related to human activity (science will never give you 100% certainty, but 95% is pretty darn good).
